Certainly! Below is a LaTeX code snippet using TikZ that represents a high-level scheme for sequential readout of word size \( b = 2 \). This example assumes you have a reference figure (`\cref{fig: unconditional_optimal_layout}`) which I'll refer to as `fig:unconditional_optimal_layout`.

```latex
\documentclass[tikz]{standalone}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric, arrows.meta}

\tikzset{
    block/.style={rectangle, draw=black, fill=white!30, text width=5em, text centered, rounded corners, minimum height=4em},
    line/.style={draw, thick, ->, >=stealth'},
}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm]

    % Nodes
    \node (start) [block] {Start};
    \node (read1) [block, below of=start] {Read Bit 1};
    \node (read2) [block, below of=read1] {Read Bit 2};
    \node (output) [block, below of=read2] {Output Word};
    \node (end) [block, below of=output] {End};

    % Arrows
    \draw [line] (start) -- (read1);
    \draw [line] (read1) -- (read2);
    \draw [line] (read2) -- (output);
    \draw [line] (output) -- (end);

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- **Nodes**: The nodes represent different steps in the process.
  - `start`: The beginning of the sequence.
  - `read1` and `read2`: Nodes representing the reading of each bit.
  - `output`: The node where the word is output.
  - `end`: The end of the sequence.

- **Edges**: Arrows connect the nodes to show the flow of the process.

This diagram provides a simple representation of the sequential readout of a word with \( b = 2 \) bits. You can compile this code using a LaTeX editor that supports TikZ, such as Overleaf or TeXShop. If you need to integrate it into your document, make sure to include the necessary packages and adjust the references accordingly.

